value.0: "Ah, <FirstName>, come for a pull of mead?" The stern expression is gone from Feran's face and he looks far more relaxed here than he did at work.
"Suit yourself, but you are missing out on a good thing."
"Never trust a <man/woman> who refuses to drink with you. That was my father's advice and I always listened to father... ha!"
"First round is on me, but then you pay for the next!"
"I take it you have further questions for me, so out with it."
"You have a good evening too. Thanks for the visit."
"He is a crude villain, in a noble guise. I would slit his throat if I... never mind. I would rather not talk about him. I just get tense again."
"She's a wonderful person, she really is. People think she's cold, but that is only because they don't understand her commitment to duty. What more can I say about her? Nothing."
"I love my job, you know? But the stress of being responsible for so many lives can really build up. That's why I come here to relax. Sometimes that's not even enough."
"Sometimes you need more than the office can give you. Sometimes you lose control. Sometimes bad things happen... Goodness, enough melancholy thoughts. What else did you want to speak of?"
"No, I have already had a few, thank you."
"Well, if you insist."
"So what were we talking about?"
"Sounds like a boring subject. Obviously boring, or else why would she have left me. I mean what drives a woman to fall in love with a cruel bastard like Sir Becket?"
"But you're a man. You probably can't answer that any better than I can. Sorry, I shouldn't go off on a rant like that."
"No, I should probably be going. I'm getting tired and not thinking straight."
"You're a woman. Tell me, do you prefer a man who treats you like a precious jewel, or like a poor dog, to be used and abused by its cruel master."
"Ah... well, that's your choice. I... I shouldn't be talking about such things anyways."
"I should probably be going anyways. Yes, I should head home."
"Yes... yes, you too. Thanks for visiting with me."
"I shouldn't... I'm letting things slip... but... maybe just one more. You really are a good listener."
"No problem, we'll just continue this another time. Good night!"
"Very kind of you. Know what? I think that I might be getting drunk. I haven't been drunk in a while. Not since... since Ellysia... left me for that bastard, Becket!"
"I was too busy doing my job, I didn't even notice he'd stolen her away... right under my nose!"
"So I got drunk! Roaring drunk! I haven't been that drunk since... well, ever really! Kind of seem to be getting that way now. And then I... I..."
"She was so beautiful... just like her sister... so much like my Ellysia... I just wanted to talk to her... I didn't mean..."
"I didn't mean to.  She was kind to me... she held me... I started to sob. She rocked me gently in her arms... then kissed my tears..."
"No! I would never do that! She was kind to me... she held me... I started to sob. She rocked me gently in her arms... then kissed my tears..."
"When I woke up next to her in the morning... I felt guilty and we got into a tremendous fight... I told her she was a pale imitation of her sister... a cruel thing to say."

"But I still loved Ellysia... still do in fact. Sometimes I just walk past Silvertongue Manor and stare at the window where we first met. But that day, Rehan, Ellysia's sister, was sobbing hysterically when I left."
"I devastated her. Later that day... oh gods... she threw herself off a cliff. Her shattered body was found by one of my men."
"No one knows why she did it. No one except me. I... I shouldn't have told you either."
"What have I done? I... I must go. I feel sick..."
Kaidala blushes and looks at you with wonder in her eyes.
"I just don't understand that! I am kind and loving and... I... I shouldn't be talking about such things."
"This is always the way with young women, or so it would seem. I have never understood this attraction."
"I treated her with kindness... and I tried to show her love, I really did. I... I shouldn't be talking about such things anyways."
"I hate the evil bastard! Enough said!"
"None of your business... sorry, but I don't want to talk about him."
"I don't want to talk about her anymore. She's my boss, and I'm sick of thinking about work."
"I too shall join you. I haven't been good and drunk in... well, not so long ago, but that isn't the point!"
"I see you are back. Did you have further questions?"
"You should come by the Mossy Tree one of these evenings for a drink."
"Short and simple: Enivid is the only candidate. You seem good enough, but Enivid has worked for years defending these people. No one else commands such respect."
"Not for all the gold in the world. I cannot think of a single thing that could convince me. Even if someone held a sword to my throat, I would vote for Enivid as they lopped off my head."
"This is a hot, thirsty subject. I shall have to make my way to The Mossy Inn tonight to quench the fire in my stomach. Was there anything else you wanted?"
"I would join you in such a toast. Perhaps if you come to The Mossy Tree tonight, you shall find me there."
"Even Sir Becket could not find one with me, and he specializes in exploiting weakness."
"Ah... nothing. It is not fit that I should speak of such things. He is a snake, that is all I will say on the subject."
"I have as much respect for that coward as I do for the foul-smelling substance I stepped in at the stables yesterday. There are those who are good leaders and those who aren't."
"Sir Becket is far below that, he couldn't lead a whore to bed, if she didn't show him the way... which plenty have, or so I have heard. The man is without honor. He is the opposite of Enivid."
"She holds an unswerving, undying loyalty to duty. She will be a good leader. There isn't really much else I can tell you about her."
"I shall try to answer any questions you have, but I am very busy, so I apologize for any abruptness in my answers."
"I do not think I would have much to offer you that you could not get from someone with less pressing matters to attend, but ask quickly."
"The Masked Man had a sharper mind than any of us had realized. If it were not for the sacrifice of the Banner to defeat the ogre, the attack might have succeeded."
"The losses may have slowed them, but they will be back, I am sure of it. And my men never found the Masked Man's corpse, so I'm not quite ready to count him among the dead yet, either."
"The Mossy Tree is a wonderful place to spend your coins or rest. I often go there myself... to relax after work."
"The Armory is in the lower keep. Glassy runs a good shop. She should be able to satisfy any outfitting needs you have."
"The Stan runs the trades guild. You can find him in his shop, The Trades, or sometimes in the trades guild office, here in the Guildhall."
"I like to keep my personal life out of the office. I would be happy to speak to you at The Mossy Inn over a glass of honey mead though."
"I don't drink much, but there is nothing like smooth mead after a long, hard day. Is there anything else?"
"Damn, I would love to go out against the Masked Man's remaining forces! But it is the position of the guild that we need to stay here to defend."
"Truth is, we are stretched just to do that. Our military has never fully recovered from the loss our army five years ago."
"And what would you like to speak of?"
"If you do somehow become the <Lord/Lady> of the Keep, then you can choose to use some of the army however you want. Short of that, I fear there is no help, for we have nothing left to give."
"We tried, but resources were scarce. With little gold, and so few trainable men or women left behind, we sent for help from the south, but only a few ever responded."
"Many of the ones who did come were of poor character, but we accepted them all. Now, with this new battle upon us, I fear that it will not be enough."
"If you can take this battle to the Masked Man's forces rather than waiting for them to return to us... you will certainly have my eternal respect and gratitude."
"The Lord of the Keep took his army off to war and never came back. No one knows what happened, though gods know we tried to find them."
"I have never heard of anything like it. Even Yenna, our mage, has never been able to trace where they went. A lot of my friends were with that army."
"I was left behind with a few others to guard the castle, should any minor problems arise. I still can see them marching off to war though it be in my dreams, now, nothing more."

"I am glad you have come to see me. I wish to apologize for the way I acted in the tavern." Feran face looks pale and drained, though you are unable to tell if it is from fear, illness, or lack of sleep.
"Goodbye, <FirstName>. I don't think I'll be going back to the tavern for a while, sorry."
"An offer? What do you mean?"
